# Courses System

Courses are the backbone of LexMastery learning experience.

Everything in the platform ultimately maps to a course structure.

---

# Product Vision

Courses must:

- Organize legal knowledge clearly
- Provide structured learning paths
- Support exam preparation journeys
- Adapt to user skill levels via AI
- Enable offline learning

Courses are not static content containers.

They are dynamic learning systems.

---

# Course Hierarchy

Each course follows:

Course

→ Modules

→ Lessons

→ Topics

→ Practice Questions

---

# Architecture

Presentation Layer

↓

CoursesController (Riverpod)

↓

CoursesState

↓

CoursesRepository

↓

Remote + Local Datasource

---

# State Management

CoursesState must include:

- loading
- error
- empty
- loaded
- refreshing

Collections:

- allCourses
- enrolledCourses
- recommendedCourses
- continueLearning
- trendingCourses

Never use booleans like isLoadingCourses.

---

# Course Types

Supported:

- Exam Preparation Courses
- Skill-based Courses
- Revision Courses
- AI-generated Adaptive Courses (future)

Each course must define:

- difficulty level
- jurisdiction (if legal)
- estimated duration
- prerequisites

---

# Enrollment Flow

1. User selects course
2. AI evaluates readiness
3. Enrollment confirmed
4. Progress initialized
5. Course added to dashboard

---

# Progress Tracking

Progress is tracked at:

- lesson level
- module level
- course level

Progress must be:

- real-time updated
- cached offline
- resumable

---

# Offline Behaviour

Courses must be fully available offline if downloaded.

Offline support includes:

- viewing course structure
- reading lessons
- accessing notes
- viewing progress

AI features are disabled offline.

---

# API Contracts

GET /courses

GET /courses/{id}

GET /courses/{id}/modules

POST /courses/enroll

POST /courses/progress

GET /courses/recommendations

---

# AI Integration

AI enhances courses by:

- recommending next course
- adjusting difficulty
- suggesting revision paths
- identifying weak modules

AI must never override user choice silently.

---

# Course Discovery

Courses must support:

- search
- filtering
- sorting
- recommendation ranking

Filters:

- difficulty
- jurisdiction
- exam type
- duration
- popularity

---

# Analytics Events

course_view

course_enroll

course_start

course_complete

course_module_complete

course_lesson_complete

course_recommendation_click

---

# UI Composition Rules

Course UI must include:

- Course card
- Progress indicator
- Continue learning button
- AI recommendation badge
- Estimated completion time

---

# Error Handling

Course failures must:

- not break dashboard
- fallback to cached courses
- allow retry

---

# Performance

Course list must load skeleton immediately.

Progress updates must be non-blocking.

---

# Security Rules

Course progress data must be:

- validated server-side
- synced securely
- not tampered with locally

---

# Testing Requirements

Unit Tests:

CoursesController

Progress calculations

Enrollment logic

Widget Tests:

Course card

Course list

Progress indicators

Integration Tests:

Course enrollment flow

Offline course access

Progress sync flow

---

# Cursor Instructions

When generating course features:

- Always use CoursesController
- Always implement progress tracking
- Always support offline access
- Always include AI recommendations
- Always include filtering and search
- Never expose raw API data to UI